21 minutes ago, Airomod said:

well it worked when i did have over 100 mods it worked fine and it didnt crash for like 2 months

Things change.  The amount of RAM used could increase in a variety of ways without your being aware of it, necessarily:  as a career progresses; if you install more mods; if any of your mods update to new versions that turn out to eat more RAM; if the stock game itself updates in a way that eats more RAM than before.

Look, regardless of anything else about your circumstances or how the computer is set up:  if you're in a place where it runs fine without mods and also it crashes when the mods are installed, there are basically only two possibilities:

  1. You're running out of RAM.
  2. There's a bug in a mod somewhere that's causing it.

There's really nothing else it could reasonably be.

Fortunately, this is pretty easy for you to diagnose:

First, Verify whether you're running out of RAM. just open up Task Manager, switch to the Processes tab, and see what KSP's memory usage is.  If you're seeing it get up to somewhere north of 3GB (e.g. 3.4GB or thereabouts) and then it crashes... yeah, you're out of RAM.  Which means either you need to run fewer mods, or else install more RAM.

There's nothing else you can do; basically you're trying to put a gallon of water in a half-gallon jug, so it's spilling.  Either pour less water or get a bigger jug. 

 

If you're running that many mods and only have 4GB of RAM, then my guess is that out-of-memory is almost certainly your problem.  However, if you check out Task Manager and you see that it's crashing when it still has a lot less than 3GB used, then possibly it may be one of the mods you're using.  In which case, that's easy to diagnose, too-- just use process of elimination to figure out which mod it is, then go ask in that mod's thread for help.  (Narrowing it down to one mod is straightforward and doesn't take too long.  Just run with half of the mods installed, then try the other half.  That'll narrow the pool of possible culprits to only half the list.  Then try running with half of those, and so forth.  This will converge pretty quickly to a single mod, since you're cutting the list in half each time.)

However... I'd strongly suggest checking the memory thing first, because that's very likely the source of your problem-- and if it is, mucking about to try to figure out "which mod is it" would be a waste of your time, because the problem is "too many mods" rather than one of them having a bug.
